GAZETTE NOTICE NO. 14017

THE ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND CO-ORDINATION ACT

( No. 8 of 1999)

THE NATIONAL ENVIRONMENT MANAGEMENT AUTHORITY

ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT STUDY REPORT FOR THE PROPOSED MEDINA PALMS LUXURY, RESIDENTIAL HOMES DEVELOPMENT ON PLOT NO. 2 IN WATAMU, MALINDI DISTRICT

PURSUANT to regulation 21 of Environmental (Impact Assessment and Audit) Regulations, the National Environment Management  Authority (NEMA)  has  received an environmental impact assessment study report for the implementation of the proposed Medina Palms Luxury, residential homes development on plot No. 2 in Watamu, Malindi District.

The proposed project involves construction and sale of 16 residential  structures  containing  50  luxury  homes  on  6.01  acres  of land.  The  proposed  project  is  located  on  Plot  No.  2  in  Watamu, Malindi District.

The  project anticipates the  following  impacts  and mitigation measures:

Possible impacts

Mitigation measures

Asbestos decommissioning impacts

-  The  construction  Contractor  in  liaison with the Project Manager should develop a site asbestos removal programme;

Possible Impacts

Mitigation Measures

HIV/AIDS and increased disease risk.

Vegetation clear / habitat / biodiversity loss.

Construction materials stockpiling and storageCoastal water contamination

Installation or upgrading of utilities.

-  Enforcing of Medical Practices;
-  Enforcing of First Aid procedures.
-  Selecting appropriate locations for construction camps;
-  Education  and  sensitisation  of  workers and the local communities on STI's;
-  Conducting of regular sensitisation campaigns, monitoring and evaluation;
-  HIV/AIDS  awareness and prevention campaign amongst workers for the duration of the contract ;
-  HIV/AIDs prevention campaigns;
-  Educating  project  workers  on  the  local culture.
-  Ensure  installation  of  informative  signs about the construction;
-  Retention and restoration of much of the original vegetation;
-  Introduction of punitive penalties by the Project Management for any breaches of vegetation protection plan;
-  Adoption of a landscape plan;
-  Collaboration between the project management and the Coast conservancy.
-  Water quality sampling and analysis for both Ocean water and Tap water ;
-  Proper stockpiling of construction materials;
-  Identification of safe storage areas.
-  Scheduling  of  trenching  works  outside of rainy season, if practical;
-  Ensure  complete  refill  of  trenches  as quickly as possible;
-  For  the  Power  supply,  the  Contractor should obtain necessary approvals / permits from KPLC;
-  Obtain  of  necessary  approvals  from  the Project Manager  for  the sourcing of water for construction works;
-  Ensuring  that pipes are not installed during the rainy season.

Fuel and chemical storage on site 

- Ensure  employees  on  site  are  aware  of the company procedures for dealing with spills and leaks;
-  In case of spillage the contractor should isolate the source of oil spill and contain the spillage;
-  Ensure supply of absorbent material;
-  All  vehicles  and  equipment  should  be kept  in  good  working  order,  serviced regularly and stored in an area approved by the Project Manager;
-  Provide security to guard against vandalism when the site is unattended;
-  Diversion of Storm water away from the fuel handling and storage areas;
-  Assemble  and  clearly  list  the  relevant emergency  telephone  contact  numbers for staff.

Possible Impacts

Mitigation Measures

Piling / building foundations

Improper waste management

Soil erosion

Air, dust and noise emissions

Impacts on turtle nesting habitats

-  Ensure restriction of pile driving activities to normal working hours (8.00am to 5.00pm);
-  Informing local residents beforehand, via notices and advisories;
-  Ensure that workers operating equipment that generate noise should be equipped with noise protection gear.
-  Adherence to the site waste management plan;
-  Ensure  that  spoil  from  excavations  is arranged  according  to  the  various  soil layers;
-  Separate hazardous from non-hazardous wastes;
-  Ensure  that  waste  is  recycled  and  reused where possible;
-  Consider cost of on-site vs. off-site recycling efforts; including reduced cost of transporting smaller volumes of materials;
-  For waste handling the Contractor should provide litter collection facilities such as bins;
-  Comply  with  the  requirements  of  the OSHA Act 2007 and Building Rules on storage of construction materials;
-  Final disposal of the site waste should be done at a location that shall be approved by the Project Manager.
-  Ensure  the  recovery  of  exposed  soils with  grass  and  other  ground  cover  as soon as possible;
-  Ensure  installation  of  temporary  bunds for exposed soil and redirection of flows;
-  Ensure  monitoring  of  areas  of  exposed soil during periods of heavy rainfall;
-  Ensure that construction related impacts like erosion and cut slope destabilization should be addressed through landscaping and grassing;
-  Ensure  Landscaping  of  the  completed site;
-  Ensure planting and irrigation of cut and fill slopes;
-  Ensure  that  all  wastewater  are  drained into approved drainage facilities.
-  Provide  dust  masks  to  all  personnel  on work site;



Ensure that

all  works  are  conducted during the day;

-  Ensure that periodic water spraying;
-  Ensure  that dust generating activities (excavation,  handling  and  transport  of soils) are not undertaken during times of strong winds;
-  Ensure that dust emissions are kept at a minimum especially in areas with human settlements.
-  Medina Palms Project Management should ensure enhancement of turtle nesting;
-  Ensure  design  and  implementation  of participatory/integrated turtle management plan.

Possible Impacts

Mitigation Measures

Timber scaffolding and form support-mangrove forest resources depletion.

Impacts of construction works on water demand

Occupational health and safety hazards

Traffic congestion/road wear and tear

Squatting

-  Ensure  that  the  use  of  local  timber  is kept to a minimum;
-  The  Project  Management  should  prefer Steel scaffolding to timber;
-  Ensure that sufficient quantities of scaffolding  are  available  for  hire  at  the time of construction;
-  Get  technical  guidance  from  the  local Kenya Forest Service Office/District Forest Officer.
-  Ensure  collaboration  with  MAWASCO in order to realise satisfactory management of water supply issues;
-  Ensure provision of adequate water storage facilities;
-  The  Project  Manager  should  monitor water consumption and utilisation;
-  Sensitise  construction  workers  on  the importance of proper water management;
-  Ensure that a comprehensive water monitoring program is implemented.
-  Ensure registration of all workplaces by the Director, Directorate of Occupational Health and Safety (DOHS) forming the basis of his work statistics;
-  Contract  a  qualified  Health  and  Safety auditor  to  conduct  annual  Health  and Safety (H&S) and fire audits and develop relevant policy for the site;
-  Ensure  establishment  of  a  Health  and Safety Committee for the project:
-  Provide a standard First Aid kit on site.
-  Effect traffic controls and cleanliness to avoid congestion and truck accidents on roads;
-  Choose traffic routes to reduce the impact in the neighbourhood;
-  For the site traffic the Contractor should ensure that they:
-  Only park in designated parking areas;
-  Don't block pedestrian routes;
-  Don't block traffic routes;
-  Obey the speed limit.
-  Ensuring  that  Staff  employment  by  the Contractor  mainly  considers  casual  and skilled personnel from the local community of Watamu area;
-  Ensure that the basis of employment of the  new  staff  is  evidence  and  ability  of residence in good condition housing;
-  Medina  Palms  Project  Management  in co-ordination  with  Malindi  Municipal Council  should  ensure  the  carrying  out of routine and strict surveillance around the work sites;
-  Ensuring that the Contractor's workforce are remunerated (Both Wages and Salaries)  in  line  with  Government  of Kenya Labour Laws and Policies.

Impacts of fuel and chemical storage on sitesite related spills.

-  Precautionary approach by ensuring that oil storage drums  / products storage areas have a smooth impermeable (concrete or thick plastic covered  in gravel) floor;

Possible Impacts

Mitigation Measures

Impacts of scuba diving and snorkelling

-  Rehabilitation of oil contaminated areas through  treatment  and  remediation  of areas affected by oil spills from machinery and storage.
-  Provision of educational and environmental  sensitization  material  on coral reefs for residents, guests  and residence staff;
-  Promulgating  Watamu  Marine  National Park (WMNP) user guidelines;
-  Installation  of  boat  mooring  buoys  at sites approved by KWS management of the WMNP for use of dive boat;
-  Banning of boat anchoring on coral substrate;
-  Banning of collection of coral reef souvenirs;
-  Instituting and supporting coral reef monitoring programme for WMNP.

The full report of the proposed project is available for inspection during working hours at:

- (a) Director General, (NEMA), Kapiti Road, off Mombasa Road, P.O. Box 67839-00200, Nairobi.
- (b) Permanent  Secretary,  Ministry  of  Environment  and  Natural Resources, N.H.I.F. Community, P.O. Box 30521, Nairobi.
- (c) Provincial Director of Environment, Coast Province.
- (d) District Environment Office, Mombasa District.

The National Environment Management Authority invites members  of  the  public  to  submit  oral  or  written  comments  within thirty  (30)  days  from  the  date  of  publication  of  this  notice  to  the Director  General,  NEMA,  to  assist  the  authority  in  the  approval process of this project.

B. M. LANGWEN,

for Director General,

National Environmental Management Authority.
